WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.000
Hello, everybody. My name is Ryan Johnson, and I'm a data science advisor here at Posit.

00:00:05.000 --> 00:00:08.000
And welcome to our first-ever enterprise community meetup,

00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:14.000
where we'll discuss an end-to-end data science workflow using Posit Team.

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:19.000
So this will be a recurring event. We'll probably have it the last Wednesday of every month.

00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:24.000
And we hope it'll serve as a good primer for those that are new to Posit Team,

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:29.000
but also help current Posit Team users become more familiar with our tools.

00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:35.000
And every month, we'll cover a different topic, and we'll highlight all three tools within Posit Team.

00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:39.000
So Posit Workbench, Posit Connect, and Posit Package Manager.

00:00:39.000 --> 00:00:46.000
And then after each presentation, we'll have a casual discussion where folks can ask us questions, Posit questions,

00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:50.000
or we can just discuss workflows with other community members.

00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:52.000
So with that, let's go ahead and get started.

00:00:52.000 --> 00:01:00.000
And I first want to start and make sure that everyone on the call is familiar with Posit Team from a high level.

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:07.000
So this is Posit Team. We're going to start up here at the top with the data scientists, the data analysts,

00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:09.000
the folks that are actually writing code.

00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:14.000
And many times their job is to create insights and to share those insights.

00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:18.000
So let's start by going to the left here and creating insights.

00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:22.000
They're going to be writing code. They can use R, Python.

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:30.000
They can use whatever IDE they want, either RStudio, JupyterLab, Jupyter Notebooks, VS Code, all within Posit Workbench.

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:35.000
So Posit Workbench is our server-based implementation of the various IDEs.

00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:39.000
And your data scientists are writing code, again, in whatever language they want.

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:46.000
So if you're within R, they might be creating things like Shiny applications, pins, R Markdown, Plumber.

00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:55.000
But if they're Python developers, they might be creating things like Flask or FastAPIs, Streamlit, Dash, Bokeh applications, Jupyter Notebooks.

00:01:55.000 --> 00:02:00.000
Maybe they're also creating Quarto documents, which is one of our newest tools.

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:07.000
So when they create content like this, it doesn't do anyone any good if you can't share it with the people that need to see it.

00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:11.000
And that's the whole purpose of Posit Connect, our second tool within Posit Team.

00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:14.000
This is our professional publishing platform.

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:20.000
And this makes it super easy to share all the cool content you see here with the people that need to see it.

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:26.000
Like your boss, decision makers, maybe yourself, maybe your friends and family.

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:28.000
You can share it with Posit Connect.

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:33.000
So for today's session, we're primarily going to live within Posit Workbench and Posit Connect.

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:38.000
But there's also one other tool we'll touch upon today, and that's Posit Package Manager.

00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:41.000
And it does pretty much as its name implies.

00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:46.000
It helps control all those great open source packages within R and Python.

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:52.000
Also, any, you know, packages you've created yourself within Workbench and Connect.

00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:57.000
And so we'll talk about all three of these tools today that, again, round out Posit Team.

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:04.000
Now, for today's session, we are actually going to live within VS Code.

00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:08.000
