00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:05.000
So just to describe what localpython is,

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:08.000
if you're creating any of your own Python packages

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:10.000
and you want to share them with your team,

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:13.000
you can upload them to your instance of Package Manager

00:14:13.000 --> 00:14:15.000
and make it super easy for anyone else

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:19.000
on your team and your company to leverage that package.

00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:21.000
And then you see pypi.

00:14:21.000 --> 00:14:24.000
And pypi is one of the largest repositories

00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:25.000
for Python packages.

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:28.000
And you can explore all the various packages

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:30.000
currently within pypi.

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:32.000
So, for example, I can search numpy,

00:14:32.000 --> 00:14:35.000
which is a pretty popular data science package

00:14:35.000 --> 00:14:37.000
within Python.

00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:38.000
We can get some information about it,

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:41.000
like how to install it, what it requires.

00:14:41.000 --> 00:14:44.000
So Python version has to be greater than 3.8.

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:46.000
What's the most recent version?

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:48.000
And some other information as well.

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:51.000
But how do I pull in numpy

00:14:51.000 --> 00:14:53.000
from this instance of Package Manager,

00:14:53.000 --> 00:14:56.000
from this pypi repository?

00:14:56.000 --> 00:14:57.000
So by selecting pypi,

00:14:57.000 --> 00:15:00.000
and you can see the name right here in the top left corner,

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:02.000
we're going to go to the Setup tab

00:15:02.000 --> 00:15:03.000
and talk a little bit more about

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:06.000
how to leverage Package Manager.

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:12.000
So I'm going to scroll down just a little bit here.

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:14.000
And you're going to see this URL.

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:18.000
Use this URL to receive the latest source packages.

00:15:18.000 --> 00:15:20.000
So when you go to install a package,

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:22.000
if you install from this URL,

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:24.000
it's going to pull in from this repository

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:27.000
on your instance of Package Manager.

00:15:27.000 --> 00:15:28.000
And, for example, this is our, again,

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:33.000
our demo environment of Posit Package Manager.

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:35.000
And then to just know a few other cool things

00:15:35.000 --> 00:15:37.000
you can do with Package Manager,

00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:39.000
you can see in the path here, Latest.

00:15:39.000 --> 00:15:40.000
By using this URL,

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:42.000
I'm always going to pull in the latest

00:15:42.000 --> 00:15:45.000
and greatest version of numpy, for example.

00:15:45.000 --> 00:15:48.000
But maybe that's not exactly what you want to do.

00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:50.000
Maybe you have a project that you worked on,

00:15:50.000 --> 00:15:51.000
you know, a year ago,

00:15:51.000 --> 00:15:53.000
and you want to go back into that project

00:15:53.000 --> 00:15:55.000
and you want to install packages

00:15:55.000 --> 00:15:57.000
as they were a year ago.

00:15:57.000 --> 00:15:59.000
And that's where this calendar comes into play.

00:15:59.000 --> 00:16:01.000
So I can go all the way back,

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:05.000
let's say December 1st, 2021.

00:16:05.000 --> 00:16:06.000
If I click on that date,

00:16:06.000 --> 00:16:08.000
you can see the URL has changed.

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:10.000
And now the date is reflected in the path.

00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:13.000
And if I install a package using this URL,

00:16:13.000 --> 00:16:19.000
it'll install it as if it's December 1st, 2021.

00:16:19.000 --> 00:16:21.000
And then if you ever want to learn

00:16:21.000 --> 00:16:23.000
how to actually leverage this URL

00:16:23.000 --> 00:16:25.000
in your instance of VS Code

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:27.000
or wherever you're doing your Python development,

00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:29.000
we have some instructions right down here

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:33.000
to install one-off packages from Package Manager

00:16:33.000 --> 00:16:35.000
or have it set more persistently.

00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:36.000
So any package you ever install

00:16:36.000 --> 00:16:39.000
will always use this URL.

00:16:39.000 --> 00:16:42.000
And that's what I've pretty much done in my environment.

00:16:42.000 --> 00:16:44.000
So that's Package Manager.

00:16:44.000 --> 00:16:48.000
So let's come back here to Connect.

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:49.000
So we've already done this step.

00:16:49.000 --> 00:16:50.000
We've installed all those packages.

00:16:50.000 --> 00:16:52.000
We made sure they're available

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:55.000
using this requirements.txt file.

00:16:55.000 --> 00:16:58.000
Let's move on to the next step.

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:00.000
And now we're going to install

00:17:00.000 --> 00:17:03.000
this rsconnect-python package.

00:17:03.000 --> 00:17:04.000
This is the actual package

00:17:04.000 --> 00:17:07.000
that's used to deploy Python content

00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:09.000
to Posit Connect.

00:17:09.000 --> 00:17:11.000
And we're going to install it using pip again.

00:17:11.000 --> 00:17:14.000
So pip install rsconnect-python-package.

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:16.000
So I'm going to go ahead and copy this command.

00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:18.000
Come back to VS Code.

00:17:18.000 --> 00:17:20.000
I'm going to clear my screen

00:17:20.000 --> 00:17:21.000
just to make it a little bit cleaner.

00:17:21.000 --> 00:17:23.000
So Control-L.

00:17:23.000 --> 00:17:28.000
I'm going to hit Paste and hit Enter.

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:29.000
Again, you can see it's pulling

00:17:29.000 --> 00:17:32.000
from that same instance of Posit Package Manager

00:17:32.000 --> 00:17:34.000
in our demo environment.

00:17:34.000 --> 00:17:35.000
And for the most part,

00:17:35.000 --> 00:17:37.000
it looks like everything that this package depends on,

00:17:37.000 --> 00:17:39.000
the package itself was already satisfied.

00:17:39.000 --> 00:17:41.000
It's already present in my environment.

00:17:41.000 --> 00:17:43.000
So that's great.

00:17:43.000 --> 00:17:44.000
So I'll clear my screen here,

00:17:44.000 --> 00:17:45.000
come back to Connect,

00:17:45.000 --> 00:17:48.000
and let's move on to the next step,

00:17:48.000 --> 00:17:50.000
which is really the last step.

00:17:50.000 --> 00:17:53.000
We are going to go ahead and deploy this application

00:17:53.000 --> 00:17:56.000
using the rsconnect-python package.

00:17:56.000 --> 00:17:58.000
Now there's a note right here.

00:17:58.000 --> 00:18:00.000
You will need to create and use an API key

00:18:00.000 --> 00:18:03.000
in order to deploy your Python application.

00:18:03.000 --> 00:18:04.000
And this is important

00:18:04.000 --> 00:18:07.000
because when you deploy to Posit Connect

00:18:07.000 --> 00:18:10.000
using this package, the rsconnect-python package,

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:13.000
Connect needs to know who is actually trying to deploy

00:18:13.000 --> 00:18:15.000
and make sure you have the necessary credentials

00:18:15.000 --> 00:18:17.000
and the privileges to actually deploy

00:18:17.000 --> 00:18:19.000
to that instance of Posit Connect.

00:18:19.000 --> 00:18:21.000
So right here is the command

00:18:21.000 --> 00:18:25.000
that we're going to use to deploy our Dash application.

00:18:25.000 --> 00:18:27.000
I'm going to go ahead and copy it,

00:18:27.000 --> 00:18:30.000
bring it on over to VS Code,

00:18:30.000 --> 00:18:31.000
again, running in Posit Workbench,

00:18:31.000 --> 00:18:32.000
and just paste it.

00:18:32.000 --> 00:18:33.000
I'm not going to run it just yet,

00:18:33.000 --> 00:18:35.000
but let's run through this command

00:18:35.000 --> 00:18:38.000
because it reads pretty easily from left to right.

00:18:38.000 --> 00:18:41.000
So we're using that rsconnect-python package,

00:18:41.000 --> 00:18:44.000
so this function right here,

00:18:44.000 --> 00:18:48.000
to deploy a Dash application to this server,

00:18:48.000 --> 00:18:51.000
this instance of Posit Connect.

00:18:51.000 --> 00:18:53.000
And then you can see this next argument,

00:18:53.000 --> 00:18:54.000
API key,

00:18:54.000 --> 00:18:57.000
and then there's some placeholder text right here.

00:18:57.000 --> 00:19:00.000
So this is where you're going to supply that API key

00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:02.000
to let Connect know that, hey,

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:04.000
it's me deploying this Dash application

00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:07.000
to that instance of Posit Connect.

00:19:07.000 --> 00:19:10.000
So where do we find this API key?

00:19:10.000 --> 00:19:11.000
Let's go back to Posit Connect,

00:19:11.000 --> 00:19:13.000
which I've already logged into.

00:19:13.000 --> 00:19:15.000
I'm going to close out of this jumpstart example

00:19:15.000 --> 00:19:18.000
because we're pretty much done with it for the most part.

00:19:18.000 --> 00:19:19.000
And I'm going to go over here

00:19:19.000 --> 00:19:22.000
to my name in the top right corner.

00:19:23.000 --> 00:19:25.000
And you'll see API keys.

00:19:25.000 --> 00:19:27.000
So you can click on API keys,

00:19:27.000 --> 00:19:31.000
and you can see I've already created about four or so API keys.

00:19:31.000 --> 00:19:33.000
If you need to create a brand new one,

00:19:33.000 --> 00:19:35.000
you just select this box right here,

00:19:35.000 --> 00:19:37.000
copy that API key,

00:19:37.000 --> 00:19:39.000
come on back over to VS Code,

00:19:39.000 --> 00:19:40.000
running in Posit Workbench,

00:19:40.000 --> 00:19:42.000
and paste it right here.

00:19:42.000 --> 00:19:43.000
Now API keys,

00:19:43.000 --> 00:19:45.000
you should always treat just like you would any password,

00:19:45.000 --> 00:19:47.000
so you want to make sure they're nice and safe.

00:19:47.000 --> 00:19:49.000
I've actually already added this to my environment,

00:19:49.000 --> 00:19:52.000
so I'm just going to delete this argument.

00:19:52.000 --> 00:19:54.000
And the rsconnect Python package

00:19:54.000 --> 00:19:57.000
will automatically detect it when it runs this command.

00:19:57.000 --> 00:19:58.000
And then the last little bit,

00:19:58.000 --> 00:20:01.000
this dot and then the forward slash right here,

00:20:01.000 --> 00:20:04.000
rsconnect will automatically detect

00:20:04.000 --> 00:20:08.000
this app.py application in the directory and deploy it.

00:20:08.000 --> 00:20:09.000
So that's it.

00:20:09.000 --> 00:20:10.000
This is the command.

00:20:10.000 --> 00:20:12.000
We'll hit enter, and we'll let it run.

00:20:16.000 --> 00:20:18.000
So it looks like I may have,

00:20:18.000 --> 00:20:20.000
so let me just check the print working directory.

00:20:22.000 --> 00:20:24.000
Let's try the command one more time.

00:20:24.000 --> 00:20:26.000
Oh, I got to delete the API key.

00:20:26.000 --> 00:20:27.000
There we go.

00:20:28.000 --> 00:20:29.000
And hit enter.

00:20:30.000 --> 00:20:31.000
There we go.

00:20:31.000 --> 00:20:33.000
So it's going through a few checks right here,

00:20:33.000 --> 00:20:34.000
like validating the server,

00:20:34.000 --> 00:20:35.000
making sure that bundle looks good,

00:20:35.000 --> 00:20:37.000
everything seems to be in order, okay.

00:20:37.000 --> 00:20:39.000
If anything's not in order,

00:20:39.000 --> 00:20:41.000
it should print some nice useful messages for you

00:20:41.000 --> 00:20:42.000
to help troubleshoot.

00:20:42.000 --> 00:20:44.000
But what's actually happening right now?

00:20:44.000 --> 00:20:46.000
Like when you deploy this application,

00:20:46.000 --> 00:20:47.000
what's going on?

00:20:48.000 --> 00:20:51.000
So for the most part, it's capturing my environment.

00:20:51.000 --> 00:20:54.000
It's looking to see what Python version am I using?

00:20:54.000 --> 00:20:56.000
What libraries am I using?

00:20:56.000 --> 00:20:58.000
What versions of the libraries?

00:20:58.000 --> 00:21:00.000
So you can see like right here, for example,

00:21:00.000 --> 00:21:02.000
all these various Python libraries

00:21:02.000 --> 00:21:04.000
and their associated versions.

00:21:04.000 --> 00:21:07.000
It's making sure Connect has those packages

00:21:07.000 --> 00:21:09.000
and the appropriate versions on the server

00:21:09.000 --> 00:21:10.000
and can replicate my environment

00:21:10.000 --> 00:21:13.000
as exactly as it's laid out here.

00:21:13.000 --> 00:21:14.000
Once it's established it can,

00:21:14.000 --> 00:21:17.000
it then deploys that dash application.

00:21:17.000 --> 00:21:20.000
So you can see deployment completed successfully.

00:21:20.000 --> 00:21:22.000
And then it gives me two links right here.

00:21:22.000 --> 00:21:25.000
We'll select that top one, click on this,

00:21:25.000 --> 00:21:29.000
and it's going to bring us right to Posit Connect.

00:21:29.000 --> 00:21:30.000
And while this is running,

00:21:30.000 --> 00:21:33.000
kind of setting up right here,

00:21:33.000 --> 00:21:34.000
you'll notice as a publisher,

00:21:34.000 --> 00:21:37.000
I have this little gear icon in the top right corner.

00:21:37.000 --> 00:21:39.000
And these are some additional controls

00:21:39.000 --> 00:21:43.000
I have as a publisher of this dash application.

00:21:43.000 --> 00:21:44.000
But here it is.

00:21:44.000 --> 00:21:48.000
This is the dash application now hosted on Posit Connect.

00:21:48.000 --> 00:21:49.000
And we can try it out.

00:21:49.000 --> 00:21:50.000
We can hover our mouse over here.

00:21:50.000 --> 00:21:53.000
Some of the plots, you can see a little pop-up.

00:21:53.000 --> 00:21:55.000
I can choose another stock.

00:21:55.000 --> 00:21:56.000
So let's try Google.

00:21:56.000 --> 00:21:59.000
You can see that one pops up as well.

00:21:59.000 --> 00:22:00.000
Scrolling down,

00:22:00.000 --> 00:22:03.000
there's a few other interactive plots and visualizations.

00:22:03.000 --> 00:22:09.000
So here I could zoom in on a specific date.

00:22:09.000 --> 00:22:10.000
This plot's pretty cool.

00:22:10.000 --> 00:22:12.000
I can select certain points

00:22:12.000 --> 00:22:14.000
and you can see those points being selected

00:22:14.000 --> 00:22:16.000
in the companion plot right to the left here,

00:22:16.000 --> 00:22:18.000
kind of a cool crosstalk feature.

00:22:18.000 --> 00:22:21.000
And then we also have a table over here as well.

00:22:21.000 --> 00:22:24.000
So this is the dash application.

00:22:24.000 --> 00:22:25.000
Now again, as a publisher,

00:22:25.000 --> 00:22:27.000
I have some additional controls.

00:22:27.000 --> 00:22:30.000
And the most important thing is I'm a publisher.

00:22:30.000 --> 00:22:34.000
How do I then share it with the people that need to see it?

00:22:34.000 --> 00:22:38.000
And that's going to be right here under access controls.

00:22:38.000 --> 00:22:40.000
Now we have it set by default

00:22:40.000 --> 00:22:42.000
to specific users or groups.

00:22:42.000 --> 00:22:44.000
And if you look right underneath,

00:22:44.000 --> 00:22:47.000
you can define those users and groups right here.

00:22:47.000 --> 00:22:50.000
I'm currently the only one that can view this content.

00:22:50.000 --> 00:22:51.000
But let's say, for example,

00:22:51.000 --> 00:22:54.000
I want to give Rachel access.

00:22:54.000 --> 00:22:57.000
Now we would be the only two that can view this content.

00:22:57.000 --> 00:22:58.000
So really tight control

00:22:58.000 --> 00:23:01.000
over who you want to share this application with,

00:23:01.000 --> 00:23:04.000
which is great, especially if you have any sensitive data.

00:23:04.000 --> 00:23:06.000
But we can be a little less strict.

00:23:06.000 --> 00:23:08.000
So if you look at the middle option right here,

00:23:08.000 --> 00:23:10.000
all users log in required.

00:23:10.000 --> 00:23:11.000
If I select this,

00:23:11.000 --> 00:23:15.000
basically as long as you can log into the Connect instance,

00:23:15.000 --> 00:23:17.000
you can view this content.

00:23:17.000 --> 00:23:20.000
So here at Posit, it's our demo environment.

00:23:20.000 --> 00:23:22.000
That's pretty much all Posit employees.

00:23:22.000 --> 00:23:24.000
They can log into the Connect instance.

00:23:24.000 --> 00:23:25.000
They can view it.

00:23:25.000 --> 00:23:27.000
But we can be even less strict

00:23:27.000 --> 00:23:31.000
and select anyone no login required.

00:23:31.000 --> 00:23:32.000
And if I do that,

00:23:32.000 --> 00:23:35.000
basically this application, this dashboard we created,

00:23:35.000 --> 00:23:38.000
when hosted on Connect, is opened up to the world.

00:23:38.000 --> 00:23:40.000
So if anyone has this URL

00:23:40.000 --> 00:23:42.000
on the top of the screen you see right here,

00:23:42.000 --> 00:23:44.000
they can view this content.

00:23:44.000 --> 00:23:46.000
Now, if you look at this URL, you can see

00:23:46.000 --> 00:23:47.000
it's not the prettiest URL.

00:23:47.000 --> 00:23:50.000
There's some random letters and numbers up here.

00:23:50.000 --> 00:23:51.000
We can change that.

00:23:51.000 --> 00:23:53.000
We can give this a more customized URL.

00:23:53.000 --> 00:23:55.000
So I can come down here to content URL

00:23:55.000 --> 00:24:00.000
and I can just say dash app and hit save.

00:24:00.000 --> 00:24:03.000
And now we have this customized URL

00:24:03.000 --> 00:24:04.000
at the bottom of my screen,

00:24:04.000 --> 00:24:06.000
which we can then share with the world

00:24:06.000 --> 00:24:10.000
and anyone can view this content.

00:24:10.000 --> 00:24:13.000
So let's talk about a few of the other options you have.

00:24:13.000 --> 00:24:15.000
Again, as a publisher,

00:24:15.000 --> 00:24:18.000
you have tight control over this dash application.

00:24:18.000 --> 00:24:21.000
And the next one we'll go to is runtime.

00:24:21.000 --> 00:24:23.000
And this is where you can control

00:24:23.000 --> 00:24:26.000
the compute resources or Python processes

00:24:26.000 --> 00:24:28.000
supporting this application.

00:24:28.000 --> 00:24:30.000
If it's a real lightweight application,

00:24:30.000 --> 00:24:33.000
doesn't require a lot of compute power,

00:24:33.000 --> 00:24:34.000
you can keep it very low.

00:24:34.000 --> 00:24:36.000
But if you have an application that's

00:24:36.000 --> 00:24:38.000
maybe crunching some large data

00:24:38.000 --> 00:24:40.000
or training a model, for example,

00:24:40.000 --> 00:24:44.000
you might want to allocate some additional Python processes.

00:24:44.000 --> 00:24:47.000
So there are Python processes supporting this application

00:24:47.000 --> 00:24:49.000
while it's running.

00:24:49.000 --> 00:24:52.000
We can define a minimum number of processes,

00:24:52.000 --> 00:24:55.000
a maximum, which you can see here is set to three.

00:24:55.000 --> 00:24:58.000
And then you have max connections per process.

00:24:58.000 --> 00:25:00.000
Now, if I share that link with somebody

00:25:00.000 --> 00:25:01.000
and they click on that link,

00:25:01.000 --> 00:25:04.000
they become a connection to this application.

00:25:04.000 --> 00:25:08.000
So by default here, I can have up to 50 connections

00:25:08.000 --> 00:25:10.000
and up to three processes.

00:25:10.000 --> 00:25:13.000
So I could support up to 150 concurrent users.

00:25:13.000 --> 00:25:15.000
Now, that may be perfect for what you need.

00:25:15.000 --> 00:25:17.000
Maybe you want to tweak it.

00:25:17.000 --> 00:25:19.000
And you can do that, again, as a publisher.

00:25:19.000 --> 00:25:21.000
You don't have to worry about your administrators

00:25:21.000 --> 00:25:23.000
and talking to them and configuring it.

00:25:23.000 --> 00:25:25.000
You can do it as a publisher.

00:25:25.000 --> 00:25:27.000
So for example, I can come in here

00:25:27.000 --> 00:25:30.000
and I can give it 10 more additional processes.

00:25:30.000 --> 00:25:32.000
And then in this configuration,

00:25:32.000 --> 00:25:35.000
I can support up to 500 concurrent users.

00:25:35.000 --> 00:25:39.000
So 50 connections per process and up to 10 processes.

00:25:39.000 --> 00:25:42.000
So again, that's how you can control it as a publisher.

00:25:44.000 --> 00:25:46.000
A few additional options here along the top,

00:25:46.000 --> 00:25:48.000
the scheduling tab.

00:25:48.000 --> 00:25:51.000
This actually does not apply to interactive content.

00:25:51.000 --> 00:25:54.000
So things like Dash, Streamlit, Bokeh,

00:25:54.000 --> 00:25:58.000
or within our ecosystem like Shiny applications.

00:25:58.000 --> 00:26:01.000
So scheduling jobs doesn't necessarily apply

00:26:01.000 --> 00:26:03.000
to interactive content.

00:26:03.000 --> 00:26:07.000
But if you are deploying things like R Markdown

00:26:07.000 --> 00:26:10.000
or Jupyter Notebooks or even Quarto documents,

00:26:10.000 --> 00:26:12.000
you can actually place code in those documents

00:26:12.000 --> 00:26:14.000
and schedule them to run.

00:26:14.000 --> 00:26:16.000
So this is great if you have any recurring jobs,

00:26:16.000 --> 00:26:18.000
maybe every morning when you come in,

00:26:18.000 --> 00:26:21.000
you can actually place them into any of those documents

00:26:21.000 --> 00:26:23.000
I just mentioned, host it on Connect,

00:26:23.000 --> 00:26:27.000
and you can schedule it to run however frequently you want.

00:26:27.000 --> 00:26:29.000
And then just to round out the last two here,

00:26:29.000 --> 00:26:32.000
tags are just for organizing your content.

00:26:32.000 --> 00:26:36.000
So if you have maybe a study or a project you're working on

00:26:36.000 --> 00:26:38.000
and there's a variety of pieces of content

00:26:38.000 --> 00:26:40.000
associated with that project,

00:26:40.000 --> 00:26:42.000
you can create a tag to help easily organize

00:26:42.000 --> 00:26:44.000
and pull up that various content types.

00:26:44.000 --> 00:26:47.000
And the last one here is VARs.

00:26:47.000 --> 00:26:51.000
If your content requires some type of privileged access

00:26:51.000 --> 00:26:54.000
to like a database or an API, for example,

00:26:54.000 --> 00:26:56.000
you can come into the VARs tab right here

00:26:56.000 --> 00:26:59.000
and supply that password or API key

00:26:59.000 --> 00:27:01.000
so the application has those credentials

00:27:01.000 --> 00:27:06.000
to access that database or API, for example.

00:27:06.000 --> 00:27:08.000
All right, so that's pretty much it.

00:27:08.000 --> 00:27:11.000
And just to recap again, what we did today,

00:27:11.000 --> 00:27:13.000
we started in Posit Workbench,

00:27:13.000 --> 00:27:15.000
we created that VS Code session,

00:27:15.000 --> 00:27:17.000
we downloaded the Dash application

00:27:17.000 --> 00:27:20.000
from the Jumpstart example hosted in Connect,

00:27:20.000 --> 00:27:22.000
so that stock example,

00:27:22.000 --> 00:27:23.000
and then we went through the process

00:27:23.000 --> 00:27:26.000
of deploying that application to Posit Connect

00:27:26.000 --> 00:27:28.000
and then sharing it with the world.

00:27:28.000 --> 00:27:29.000
And as we did that,

00:27:29.000 --> 00:27:32.000
we were installing packages from our instance

00:27:32.000 --> 00:27:34.000
of Posit Package Manager.

00:27:34.000 --> 00:27:37.000
So hopefully this Posit team overview was helpful

00:27:37.000 --> 00:27:38.000
and we're just going to go ahead

00:27:38.000 --> 00:27:40.000
and open it up to any questions from the audience,

00:27:40.000 --> 00:27:42.000
general discussion,

00:27:42.000 --> 00:27:45.000
and we'd be happy to answer any questions anybody has.

